    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Lochmoor Waterway Estates began as an unincorporated community during Florida's post‑World War II land boom, driven by military bases and northern retirees.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lochmoor_waterway_estates_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The neighborhood’s homes are mostly low‑density, single‑family houses built in the 1960s and 1970s, many with canal views.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        21
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lochmoor_waterway_estates_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "It sits on the west bank of the tidal Caloosahatchee River, directly across from Fort Myers, the county seat.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        27
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lochmoor_waterway_estates_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Bridges over the Caloosahatchee connect Lochmoor to the wider region, making the riverside location a key transit point.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        28
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lochmoor_waterway_estates_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "About a quarter of the 3.21‑square‑mile area is water, largely from the river and local canals.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/lochmoor_waterway_estates_florida"
    },
    {
